1️⃣ Application Architecture
Application Architecture describes how different parts of an application are structured and how they communicate with each other.
A typical web application architecture usually contains three main components:

1. Frontend (User Interface – UI)
The Frontend is the visual part of the application that users interact with.
It runs inside the web browser.
Displays buttons, forms, dashboards, and pages.
Sends user requests to the backend.
Example technologies: Angular, React, Vue
👉 Example: When a user clicks “Login”, the request is sent from the frontend to the backend.

2. Backend (Business Logic Layer)
The Backend is responsible for processing requests and implementing business logic.
Responsibilities include:
Handling API requests
Processing user input
Applying business rules
Communicating with the database
Example technologies: Java, Node.js, Python

3. Database (Data Storage Layer)
The Database stores all the application data.
Examples of stored data:
User accounts
Transactions
Application logs
Product information
Example technologies: MySQL, PostgreSQL, MongoDB
Application Request Flow
The communication flow in a typical web application is:
User → Frontend → Backend → Database
Example flow:
User submits a login form
Frontend sends request to Backend API
Backend checks user credentials in the Database
Database returns result
Backend sends response to Frontend
Frontend shows Login Success / Failure

2️⃣ Tech Stack of an Application
A Tech Stack refers to the collection of technologies used to build and run an application.
It includes technologies for:
Frontend development
Backend processing
Database storage
Application servers

Example Tech Stack
Layer	Technology	Purpose
Frontend	Angular 16	Builds the user interface
Backend	Java 17	Handles business logic & APIs
Database	MySQL Server 8.5	Stores application data
Web Server	Tomcat 9.0	Runs the Java application
What is a Dependency?

A Dependency is any software required for the application to run properly.
Example dependencies for this application:
Java Runtime
Angular Framework
MySQL Database
Tomcat Server
To run the application without Docker, every machine must install these dependencies manually.

3️⃣ Application Environments
In real-world software development, applications are not deployed directly to production.
Instead, they pass through multiple environments for testing, validation, and quality assurance.
Each environment serves a specific purpose.

1️⃣ DEV (Development Environment)
The Development Environment is used by developers.
Purpose:
Writing code
Building new features
Fixing bugs
Integrating modules
This environment may be unstable because developers frequently change code.

2️⃣ SIT (System Integration Testing)
The System Integration Testing (SIT) environment is used to test whether all modules of the system work together correctly.
Focus areas:
API communication
Database connectivity
Integration between services
Example:
Frontend calling Backend APIs.

3️⃣ UAT (User Acceptance Testing)
The User Acceptance Testing (UAT) environment is used by the client or business stakeholders.
Purpose:
Verify that the system meets business requirements
Validate real-world scenarios
At the end of UAT, the client decides:
Go / No Go
Meaning:
Go → Deploy to production
No Go → Fix issues

4️⃣ PILOT Environment
The Pilot Environment is a pre-production testing stage.
Characteristics:
Application is tested with limited real users
Helps detect issues before full production launch
Example:
A new feature is released to 10% of users first.

5️⃣ PROD (Production Environment)
The Production Environment is the live system where real users access the application.
Characteristics:
High stability
High security
High availability
Any failure in production can affect real customers.

4️⃣ Why We Need Docker Even When We Already Have Application Architecture
Even if we have a well-designed application architecture and a defined tech stack, running the application across multiple machines can still be difficult.
Why?
Because the application depends on many software dependencies.
Example dependencies:
Java
Angular
MySQL
Tomcat

Specific library versions
Every environment must install these dependencies correctly.

Problems Without Docker
1️⃣ Dependency Installation Errors
Manual installation in every environment can cause mistakes.
Example:
A developer forgets to install a required library.
Result → Application fails to run.

2️⃣ Version Compatibility Issues
Different machines may use different software versions.
Example:
DEV machine → Java 17
Server → Java 11
Result → Application may crash or behave unexpectedly.

3️⃣ Environment Differences
An application may run perfectly on the developer's laptop but fail on the server.
This is known as the famous problem:

“It Works on My Machine”
5️⃣ How Docker Solves This Problem
Docker solves these problems by packaging the application and its dependencies together into a container.
A Docker Container includes:
Application Code
Runtime Environment (Java)
Required Libraries
Configuration Files
Benefits of Docker

1️⃣ Consistent Environment
The application runs exactly the same on every machine.
DEV = SIT = UAT = PROD

2️⃣ No Manual Dependency Installation
We don't need to install:
Java
Angular
MySQL
Tomcat
Everything is already inside the container.

3️⃣ Faster Deployment
Instead of installing many tools, we simply run:
Docker Container → Application starts immediately
Without Docker
Every machine must install:
Java
Angular
MySQL
Tomcat
Manual setup = Time consuming + Error prone

With Docker
We just run:
Docker Container
Everything required is already packaged inside it.
